{"id":"project-LICHEN-b4xi","title":"gradient.c: lichen_gradient_update may decrement count below zero","description":"File: lichen/subsys/lichen/routing/gradient.c
Lines: 166-177

In lichen_gradient_update(), when evicting an LRU entry:

    struct lichen_gradient_entry *slot = find_free_slot(table);
    if (slot == NULL) {
        slot = find_lru(table);
        if (slot == NULL) {
            return -ENOMEM;
        }
        table->count--;  // <-- Decrement for eviction
    }

    memcpy(slot, entry, sizeof(*slot));
    slot->valid = true;
    slot->last_used_ms = now_ms;
    table->count++;  // <-- Increment for new entry

This is correct for the eviction case. However, if count tracking elsewhere gets out of sync (e.g., due to a bug in lichen_gradient_remove or lichen_gradient_remove_via), this decrement could underflow.

The issue is that find_lru() checks slot->valid, but table->count may not accurately reflect the number of valid entries. If count < actual_valid_count, the decrement is fine. But if count > actual_valid_count (due to a prior bug), eventually count could underflow when all slots appear full but count says otherwise.

Consider using atomic operations or adding a sanity check: 'if (table->count > 0) table->count--;'","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","owner":"me@mark.atwood.name","created_at":"2026-07-12T06:51:28.985223Z","created_by":"Mark Atwood","updated_at":"2026-07-12T06:51:28.985255Z"}

